<doc id="1158578" wikidata="Q724751" url="?curid=1158578" title="Jayadeva (mathematician)">
<text>Jayadeva (c. 1000 CE) was an Indian mathematician, who further developed the cyclic method (Chakravala method) that was called by Hermann Hankel &quot;the finest thing achieved in the theory of numbers before Lagrange (18th century)&quot;. He also made significant contributions to combinatorics.

Jayadeva&#x27;s works are lost, and he is known only from a 20-verse quotation in Udaya-divakara &quot;Sundari&quot; (c. 1073), a commentary on Bhaskara I&#x27;s &quot;Laghu-bhaskariya&quot;. This means that Jayadeva must have lived sometime before 1073, possibly around 1000 CE.

==See also==
*List of Indian mathematicians

